observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management require the MA to:
a) prepare and maintain complete SLs for the receivable accounts, consequently, prepare an aging schedule in accordance with Section 111 of PD No. 1445 to monitor the collectability of the Accounts Receivable and be able to determine the potential impairment losses to be recognized in the books to present fairly the Receivable accounts in the FS;
b) prepare and maintain complete SLs for the Payable accounts, and thereafter prepare an aging schedule to establish the validity and existence of the accounts payable and determine dormant accounts;
c) revert to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund the accounts payable which has been in the books for more than two years and with unfounded claims; and
d) exert utmost effort in locating documents that will provide information as to details of long outstanding payables and receivables.

We recommended that the Management:
a) instruct the designated LDRRM officer to (i) plan properly and monitor the timely and full implementation of LDRRM Fund towards the achievement of the objectives of the RA No. 10121 to ensure the Municipality’s preparedness in times of calamity; and (ii) submit on a monthly basis the Report on Resources and Utilization in accordance to Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular no. 2012-002;
b) ensure that the amount corresponding to the current year’s unutilized appropriation, except those for capital outlay, is transferred to the STF at the end of the year;
c) establish the correct unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE of previous years that shall be reported to the STF, provide the Audit Team of a statement of how the amount was arrived, and prepare and submit the necessary JEV to reflect the adjustment; and
d) reconcile the difference noted and inconsistencies in the Accomplishment Reports and MDRRMF Utilization Report submitted by the MDRRMO and the FS.

We recommended the Management to instruct the MA to:
(a) prioritize the reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments that needs to be adjusted in the books;
(b) prepare and maintain the required SLs to determine at any time the details and status of the intra-agency accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
reconcile the difference amounting to ₱46,509.70 noted between the amount set up as SET receivable in the Municipality’s books and the amount computed based on the List of Taxpayers provided by the MTO;
reconcile the difference noted between the amount credited to the RPT and SET receivables and the amount collected based on the Summary of RPT provided by MTO;
prepare necessary adjusting entries to exclude the amount of penalties recorded as part of RPT and SET receivables; and
exclude penalties in the RPT and SET receivables account and comply with Sections 20 and 23 Chapter 3 Volume 1 MNGAS for LGUs, the definition of taxes in the IPSAS 23, and Circular no. 2015-009 in setting up the amount of RPT and SET receivables at the beginning of the year, to facilitate the fair presentation of the RPT and SET receivables in the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Management agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

strictly enforce settlement of all unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2020;

stop the granting of additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled/liquidated to avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances; 

remind the officers and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period; and

issue demand letters to enforce/require the immediate settlement and/or refund of the amount advanced, and enforce the withholding of salaries of those who fail to settle/liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period after the demand.

We recommended and the Management agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

strictly enforce settlement of all unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2019;

stop the granting of additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled/liquidated to avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances;

remind the officers and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period; and

issue demand letters to enforce/require the immediate settlement and/or refund of the amount advanced, and enforce the withholding of salaries of those who fail to settle/liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period after the demand.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive:

a) coordinate with the Liga ng mga Barangay and encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the Solid Waste Management Program of the Municipality by educating their respective constituents through Information Education Campaign (IEC) on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes and the importance of their participation in the implementation of various SWM programs;

b) require the MENRO to (a) comply with the requirements of RA No. 9003 on waste segregation by placing trash bins and/or garbage receptacles with proper labels on the designated garbage collection area and other public places and collect only those wastes which are properly segregated; and (b) see to it that the operation of the open dumpsite is properly controlled and complied with as provided in Section 2 of Rule XIII of the IRR of RA 9003;

c) enforce Municipal Ordinance No. 2006-124 as amended by MO No. 2017-206 on segregation of wastes and firmly impose fines and penalties against violators or prohibited acts to ensure compliance of all and to provide additional funding for solid waste management activities; and

d) prioritize the implementation of programs and projects identified in the Solid Waste Management Plan and Annual Investment Plan pertaining to solid waste management.

We recommended the Management to instruct the:

a) Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to closely monitor and supervise the full implementation of the proposed projects within the targeted period in order to fully realize the objectives of the 20% Development Fund and;

b) Municipal Budget Officer, Municipal Accountant and MPDC to ensure the inclusion and re-appropriation of the savings amounting to ₱1,364,666.30 in the preparation of the ensuing year’s Annual Investment Plan for the 20% Development Fund in order to augment the much needed fund for the attainment of socio-economic development and environmental management outcome of the Municipality.

