We recommended and Management agreed to:
exercise prudence in the utilization of funds for meals and snacks specially during meetings and  observe the limitations for such expenditures as prescribed by law;
observe proper procedures in the procurement of meals and snacks as prescribed in RA No. 9184;
ensure that all transactions are supported with complete documentations before payment; and
look into the frequency and necessity of the rendition of various activities of the agency and undertake measures to minimize its expenditures for meals served during the conduct of meetings and other activities.   The number of persons involved whether participants or resource persons and the exclusion of non-participants in an undertaking from those being served  with snack and meals are among the aspects to be given due consideration.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
require the Municipal Social Welfare Development Officer to ensure that all plans for CICL are implemented. Outsourcing or partnership with private organizations and entities that provide financial assistance for the implementation of LCPC programs is encouraged;
instruct all departments in the preparation of PPAs to make reference to RA 9344 with the full consideration that such activities are designed solely for Children at risk and Children in Conflict with the Law and not for children in general.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and Management agreed to:
require strict enforcement/implementation of Municipal Ordinance No. 2006-124 specifically on segregation of wastes; intensify the campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy; and firmly impose fines and penalties against violators of prohibited acts to ensure compliance of all and to provide additional funding for solid waste management activities;
ensure active participation of all households, commercial businesses/ establishments, institutions and market vendors in segregation and proper waste disposal at source;
take appropriate action necessary for the improvement of the existing Material Recovery Facility (MRF) of the Municipality to make it operational and see to it that the operation of the open dumpsite is properly controlled and complied with the provisions of RA 9003; and
prioritize the implementation of programs and projects identified in the Solid Waste Management Plan and Annual Investment Plan pertaining to solid waste management.

In view of the above representations, we recommended that the Management:
direct the GAD focal person/official, with the aim of ensuring that the genuine local gender issues will be addressed, to conduct study, data gathering, and coordination with barangays, social welfare/development official/s and the Philippine National Police to identify activities that affect the residents, especially the welfare of women and/or violations committed against them that are vital for the formulation of programs/projects that have to be in accordance with the provisions of the republic act;
observe strict adherence to the guidelines set forth in the preparation of Annual GAD Plan and Budget as provided for under PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 as well as the relevant amendments from Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2016-01.

provide the necessary fund for LCPC to ensure that all plans for CICL are implemented. Outsourcing or partnership with private organizations and entities that provide financial assistance for the implementation of LCPC programs is encouraged;  

instruct the MBO to check and review whether amount allotted for LCPC equivalent to 1% of IRA and the identified PPAs are in conformance with DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2012-120 dated July 4, 2012; and 

instruct all those concerned in the preparation of PPAs to make reference to Republic Act No. 9344 with the full consideration that such activities are designed solely for Children at risk and Children in Conflict with the Law and not for children in general.

We reiterated the following recom-mendations:

Exert extra effort to be able to produce the documents to prove ownership of these vehicles; 

Secure the original OR/CR of the subject vehicles with green plates together with Deed of Conveyance and/or Affidavit from Mr. Jonathan Garcia, former Mayor of Mogpog and owner of Suzuki Multicab with plate number XTC 779,  transferring all his rights and privileges over the subject vehicle to the Municipality of Mogpog to facilitate its registration;

Require the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with LTO for the immediate registration of the motor vehicles; and 

Provide budget for the payment of registration fees of the subject vehicles with LTO.

We recommended that the:
MAO and MTO immediately reconcile their records to determine the actual balances of PPE in order to present fairly the balances of the affected accounts at year-end. Any discrepancies between the RPCPPE and the accounting records should be investigated and adjusted accordingly;
Inventory Committee strictly comply with the provisions of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System, Volume I on the submission of RPCPPE.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer coordinate with one another for proper accounting and reporting of RPT and SET as prescribed under the NGAS;
Municipal Treasurer coordinate and reconcile its records with that of the Municipal Assessor to determine any changes and/updates in the real properties;
Municipal Accountant justify the reported negative balance of SET Receivable; and
MTO to submit a Certified List of Taxpayers to support the amount recorded.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the:
Municipal Treasurer pursue extensive collection of water service fee from delinquent water subscribers to augment the income of the Municipality and being the concerned official, must take appropriate actions on the matter;
Municipal Administrator must ensure that the present water pumps were in good operating conditions to be able to provide adequate water supply for the subscribers and see to it that all subscribers are installed with water meters;
once installed, require periodic inspection and calibration to ensure their reliability and accuracy to determine accurate consumption of every household.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:
Drivers of the service vehicles properly accomplish the Daily Trip Tickets and attached to the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Travel regularly;
Municipal Administrator to install control measures on the disbursements of fuel to minimize wasteful, excessive and unnecessary expenditures for fuel consumption and ensure strict adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61 for the proper accounting and control of fuel consumption of government vehicles and other machineries and equipment of the Municipality.

We recommended that the GAD Focal Person:
observe strict adherence to the guidelines for the preparation of Annual GAD Plan and Budget and corresponding Accomplishment Report and for the submission of copies thereof to the Auditor as provided in PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 and COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014; and
ensure that the Annual GAD Plan and Budget was approved by the DILG before incorporating to the Annual Budget so that the programs that will be implemented under GAD are directed to improving the municipal government’s capacity for gender mainstreaming, gender issues and/or promoting gender equality;

In view of the foregoing, we recommended the Management to:

Require the BAC to submit documents supporting the                               post-qualification process as well as the BAC Resolution showing validation of the legal, technical and financial document submitted by the bidder; 

Strictly abide the standards set forth by RA No. 9184 and its IRR and other relevant laws in all the procurement projects of the Municipality.

We reiterated our recommendations to:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the granting of financial assistance to various non-governmental organizations/peoples’ organization that are treated as Donation (878) to Due from NGOs/POs (139);

Direct the Municipal Account to prepare the appropriate adjusting entries as Prior Year’s adjustments to reclassify the expense account and to establish receivable account for those donations granted to NGOs/POs, 

Require the Municipal Accountant to demand submission of the liquidation reports/accomplishment reports from recipient non-governmental organizations/peoples’ organizations as basis for closing the receivable account; 

Submit Memoranda of Agreement between respective NGOs/POs to support the payments;  and 

Stop granting subsidy to NGOs/POs that do not clearly define the projects as enumerated under COA Circular No. 2007-001 dated October 25, 2007
